Ask HN: Open-source license that limits usage by ML algorithms?
text: Let’s imagine I want to publish my awesome open source project so that others can contribute, use it for personal usage and all those good things. But I want to explicitly deny usage of my project as training data for any ML algorithm (e.g., copilot, chatGPT, etc.). Does any license exist already to address this? If not, can I just state that as an extra paragraph in my LICENSE file?

Show HN: Domain Name Search with AI
text:
In my exploration of OpenAI, I just created a domain-name search that takes business description as an input, and generates interesting domain names for it. It then uses DNSimple API to check if .com is available.

In my view it is a much easier way to find a suitable domain, as the AI thinks of a much large pool of possible names than my own brain. SmartyNames found its own name, using the tool itself.

Hope you enjoy it! https://smartynames.com/

Thanks a lot for your insights!

title: Ask HN: When will ChatGPT become open?
text:
Every third post I read in HN is about chatGPT and how much fun and creativity people are getting out of it. However it's unlikely OpenAI will just release the model like they did with whisper due to the size and commercial constraints. To adapt this technology to different industries like education / healthcare, it needs to be open to experimentation and tinkering.

So I was wondering, when will chatGPT have it's stable diffusion moment? Is it possible for any decent machine to run these kinds of models?

Show HN: Export ChatGPT conversations as GitHub gists
text:
Made a bookmarklet for sharing ChatGPT logs as gists. It has markdown support so it can render tables, code blocks, and all the usual formatting (except maybe footnotes).

Example: https://gist.github.com/tkanarsky/8858d339f02567d5cd25fcf9c4...

It was pretty tricky finding the right selectors to use as the UI is just full of React div-soup with zero semantic meaning. I eventually settled on some CSS classes that work well for now, but that might change at any time in the future. No guarantee of stability :)

One thing it's missing right now is code highlighting -- I haven't had the time to translate the language names from hljs -> markdown.
